00:00:04.569 --> 00:00:09.450
One of our biggest problems we face when travelling
in space, is the atrophy our bodies endure

00:00:09.450 --> 00:00:13.769
while in microgravity. The astronauts on the
international space station have to exercise

00:00:13.769 --> 00:00:18.220
several times a day to maintain their bone
and muscle strength. But is there an alternative?

00:00:18.220 --> 00:00:21.810
Can we create Artificial Gravity?
I’m sure you have seen the idea before in

00:00:21.810 --> 00:00:27.250
movies like 2001: A Space Odyssey where the
entire space station spins to create an artificial

00:00:27.250 --> 00:00:32.820
gravity. The people inside can now walk comfortably
just like just on earth. It does this by exploiting

00:00:32.820 --> 00:00:36.050
centrifugal force.
Now it seems that whenever someone mentions

00:00:36.050 --> 00:00:40.219
centrifugal force, angry mobs will show up
in the comment section. Declaring it isn’t

00:00:40.219 --> 00:00:43.190
real. Which just isn’t the case. Let’s
see why

00:00:43.190 --> 00:00:47.750
NASA developed this huge centrifuge to test
the possibility of simulated gravity back

00:00:47.750 --> 00:00:52.440
in the 1960s. Here we are looking from inertial
frame of reference, that just means we are

00:00:52.440 --> 00:00:56.109
looking from outside perspective and we can
clearly see that there is no force pulling

00:00:56.109 --> 00:01:00.260
this guy outwards. It is just his inertia
carrying him forward, and the floor he is

00:01:00.260 --> 00:01:04.269
walking on provides the centripetal force
to prevent him from flying off.

00:01:04.269 --> 00:01:08.840
But what happens if our reference frame moves
with the astronaut. This is called a rotating

00:01:08.840 --> 00:01:13.659
reference frame, or a non-inertial reference
frame. To him, the rest of the world is moving,

00:01:13.659 --> 00:01:19.000
and he is standing stationary. In this reference
frame centrifugal force is absolutely a real

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:23.490
and measurable force, pushing him downwards
just like gravity. The only thing that is

00:01:23.490 --> 00:01:26.670
fictitious is his perception of what is causing
it.

00:01:26.670 --> 00:01:31.150
This occurs because in physics and engineering,
we must balance forces. The system has to

00:01:31.150 --> 00:01:35.920
be in equilibrium. Newton’s third law states
for every action there is an equal and opposite

00:01:35.920 --> 00:01:38.939
reaction.
So if centripetal force exists in this reference

00:01:38.939 --> 00:01:43.240
frame there has to be a force pushing him
outwards. That is centrifugal force. And the

00:01:43.240 --> 00:01:47.869
moment the rotation stops it vanishes again.
So if this works so well, why haven’t we

00:01:47.869 --> 00:01:52.680
seen a spinning space station yet? Well one
problem is size. To make this practical we

00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:57.090
need a massive ship, which would be incredibly
expensive to get into orbit.

00:01:57.090 --> 00:02:01.289
The acceleration your body will experience
is directly proportional to speed and radius

00:02:01.289 --> 00:02:06.380
of the space station. We can calculate the
gravity Space Station V from 2001: A Space

00:02:06.380 --> 00:02:11.280
Odyssey would generate with some pretty simple
math. The space station V had a diameter of

00:02:11.280 --> 00:02:15.040
300 meters and spun on it’s axis once every
60 seconds.

00:02:15.040 --> 00:02:18.769
That would put its gravity at about the same
as the moons. For it to have a gravity similar

00:02:18.769 --> 00:02:21.540
to earths it would need to spin once every
24 seconds.

00:02:21.540 --> 00:02:25.780
If were to make this a realistic size, let’s
say the same size as the international space

00:02:25.780 --> 00:02:30.419
station. It would need to spin once every
10 seconds. This would probably be pretty

00:02:30.419 --> 00:02:34.620
disorientating, just ask Sandra bullock.
Another problem we face on smaller stations

00:02:34.620 --> 00:02:38.650
like this, is the gradient in acceleration
you would experience. Because the acceleration

00:02:38.650 --> 00:02:42.840
is directly proportional to the distance to
the rotational center, your head will experience

00:02:42.840 --> 00:02:46.859
less artificial gravity than your feet. This
would force the blood to your feet, just like

00:02:46.859 --> 00:02:50.480
when you spin a bucket of water around. This
effect will diminish with a larger stations.

00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:54.400
So to make a practical space station with
artificial gravity the station would have

00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:59.630
to be huge, which is simply too expensive.
Besides, the ISS is most valuable to us as

00:02:59.630 --> 00:03:04.530
a laboratory to test the effects of microgravity.
